atDirectives.description:
Import Tailwind CSS v4 into your stylesheet. In v4 you use a single CSS import instead of separate `@tailwind` directives:
```css
@import "tailwindcss";
```
You can also import specific layers:
```css
@import "tailwindcss/theme";
@import "tailwindcss/utilities";
```

Define your design tokens as CSS variables. The `@theme` directive is the primary way to customize Tailwind v4, replacing the `theme` key in `tailwind.config.js`:
```css
@theme {
  --color-primary: oklch(0.7 0.15 200);
  --font-display: "Inter", sans-serif;
  --spacing-lg: 2rem;
}
```
All tokens become CSS custom properties available throughout your stylesheet.

Register a reusable custom variant that can be used as a modifier prefix with any utility class. Supports a shorthand form for single selectors:
```css
@custom-variant theme-midnight (&:where([data-theme="midnight"] *));
```
Or a block form with `@slot` for complex variants involving multiple rules or media queries:
```css
@custom-variant any-hover {
  @media (any-hover: hover) {
    &:hover {
      @slot;
    }
  }
}
```
Once defined, the variant works like any built-in modifier:
```html
<button class="theme-midnight:bg-black any-hover:opacity-75"></button>
```

Inline any existing utility classes into your own custom CSS. Useful when you find a common utility pattern you'd like to extract:
```css
.btn {
  @apply px-4 py-2 rounded font-semibold;
}
```

Apply Tailwind variants to styles in custom CSS, or define reusable custom variants. Use it to apply an existing variant to a block of CSS:
```css
.card {
  background: white;
  @variant dark {
    background: black;
  }
}
```
Or define a new custom variant:
```css
@variant hocus {
  &:hover, &:focus {
    @slot;
  }
}
```

Register a custom utility class that integrates with Tailwind's variant system and `@apply`. Replaces the `@layer utilities` pattern from v3:
```css
@utility tab-4 {
  tab-size: 4;
}
```
Functional utilities (with values) use a `--value()` function:
```css
@utility tab-* {
  tab-size: --value(integer);
}
```

Explicitly specify source files or directories for Tailwind to scan for utility class names. Useful when auto-detection misses files outside standard project directories:
```css
@source "../node_modules/@my-company/ui/**/*.js";
```
Or disable auto-detection entirely:
```css
@source none;
```

Load a Tailwind CSS plugin directly from your CSS file. Accepts a package name or relative path:
```css
@plugin "@tailwindcss/typography";
@plugin "./my-local-plugin";
```
Pass configuration options using `with`:
```css
@plugin "@tailwindcss/typography" {
  --tw-prose-body: var(--color-gray-700);
}
```

Load a JavaScript-based `tailwind.config.js` for backwards compatibility with v3 projects. Should be placed after `@import`:
```css
@import "tailwindcss";
@config "./tailwind.config.js";
```
Not needed for new v4 projects — prefer CSS-based configuration with `@theme`.

Add styles to a named CSS cascade layer. Tailwind v4 exposes `theme`, `base`, `components`, and `utilities` layers:
```css
@layer base {
  h1 { font-size: 2rem; }
}
@layer components {
  .card { border-radius: 0.5rem; }
}
```
For custom utilities that need variant support, prefer `@utility` over `@layer utilities`.

**Deprecated in Tailwind v4.** Use `@variant` with a breakpoint name instead:
```css
/* v4 preferred */
@variant sm {
  .foo { color: red; }
}

/* v3 syntax (still works via compat) */
@screen sm {
  .foo { color: red; }
}
```
